<subSubSection id="16E66509FE28FF936DA0FAA05215B37C" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="5E433682FE28FF936DA0FAA051E5B044" blockId="7.[151,404,1303,1330]" box="[151,404,1303,1330]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">
<heading id="050B81EEFE28FF936DA0FAA051E5B044" bold="true" box="[151,404,1303,1330]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" reason="1">
<emphasis id="6C88EA90FE28FF936DA0FAA051E5B044" bold="true" box="[151,404,1303,1330]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">
The 
<taxonomicName id="99FC4D01FE28FF936DF8FAA05132B047" authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[207,323,1303,1330]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strigulata">
<emphasis id="6C88EA90FE28FF936DF8FAA05132B047" bold="true" box="[207,323,1303,1330]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">strigulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5E433682FE28FF936DA0FAE85215B37C" blockId="7.[151,1436,1375,1690]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">
Externally, species are characterized by the cream white forewing with a couple of oblique distal markings on the costal margin (
<figureCitation id="C6C72A07FE28FF936C0CFA34510AB0E8" box="[315,379,1411,1437]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); a white frontal tuft. In the male genitalia, the uncus is comprised of two large, distally pointed lateral lobes; the gnathos without a central plate, comprised of two very large lateral arms and a long, slender caudal process; and the vinculum with a membranous, laterally thickened juxta connected to the base of caudal process of the gnathos (
<figureCitation id="C6C72A07FE28FF936C10FA585119B37C" box="[295,360,1519,1545]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Female is unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="16E66509FE28FF936DF0F9A454F3B3EC" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" type="description">
<paragraph id="5E433682FE28FF936DF0F9A4514CB300" blockId="7.[151,1436,1375,1690]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">
The 
<taxonomicName id="99FC4D01FE28FF936DCDF9A45116B358" authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[250,359,1555,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strigulata">
<emphasis id="6C88EA90FE28FF936DCDF9A45116B358" box="[250,359,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">strigulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group is distinguished from other groups of the Oriental (or Neotropical) 
<taxonomicName id="99FC4D01FE28FF936991F9A45521B358" box="[1190,1360,1555,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6C88EA90FE28FF936991F9A45521B358" box="[1190,1360,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">Pseudopostega</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the combination of large, distally pointed lobes of the uncus and the long, slender caudal process of the gnathos in the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5E433682FE28FF936DF0F9C854F3B3EC" blockId="7.[151,1436,1375,1690]" box="[199,1154,1663,1690]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">
Distribution. Currently the group is comprised of a single species from 
<collectingCountry id="26EB7612FE28FF936ED0F9C85450B3EC" box="[999,1057,1663,1689]" name="India" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">India</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="C6C72A07FE28FF936907F9C85400B3EC" box="[1072,1137,1663,1689]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
